The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Bharat Earth Movers Ltd (BEML) has clocked a 541 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 178.27 crore for 2004-05 compared with Rs 27.80 crore in the previous fiscal. The company board has recommended a 100 per cent dividend, inclusive of a 15 per cent interim dividend, for the reporting year. The company has also reported a 139.11 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 12.41 crore for the first quarter ended June 30 against Rs 5.19 crore for the same quarter in previous fiscal.

 Ramco Industries has reported a 19 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 28.84 crore in 2004-05 against Rs 24.19 crore in the previous fiscal on the back of a 23 per cent increase in turnover at Rs 190.78 crore. The company had clocked a Rs 154.67-crore turnover in 2003-04. The board has recommended a final dividend of 40 per cent in addition to an interim payout of 30 per cent paid earlier.

 Bharat Overseas Bank plans to increase its branches in the country to 100 in the next two months from 94 at present and will soon commence distribution of mutual fund schemes and bonds through its branches. The bank has recently opened its 94th branch in Chennai.

 HMT has posted a net profit of Rs 5.98 crore for 2004-05 compared with a net loss of Rs 7.97 crore in the previous year. The total income of the company has increased to Rs 293.88 crore from Rs 180.33 crore in the previous fiscal.

 Finolex Industries will pay a 30 per cent dividend to its shareholders for 2004-05. The annual general meeting has approved the payout proposal, which would cost the company Rs 37.210 crore.

 Time Square Investments Pvt Ltd and Seshasayee Paper amp; Boards have increased their stakes in Ponni Sugars (Erode) Ltd to 40.46 per cent by acquiring 2.70 lakh shares from Ipicol of Orissa. Time Square directly holds 4.11 per cent in Ponni Sugars, while Seshasayee Paper holds 16.90 per cent.

 Sudarshan Chemical Industries has recommended a final dividend of 30 per cent to its shareholders for 2004-05. The company had already paid a 30 per cent interim dividend in February.

 Uniroyal Textile Industries will expand and diversify into real estate and pharmaceuticals. The company will raise Rs 2.35 crore by issuing 23.5 lakh shares of Rs 10 each to the promoters.

 Woodland, the footwear brand, has introduced its summer collection. Priced between Rs 1,695 and Rs 2,295, the collection comprises lace-up shoes and closed sandals.

